04847nam a22008895i 9780823272266DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232722667 a10.1515/97808232722662doi  a(DE-B1597)555257  a(OCoLC)966458148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR868.I615bS76 2017eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.8092231 aStout, Daniel M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCorporate Romanticism :bLiberalism, Justice, and the Novel /cDaniel M. Stout. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLit Z00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Personification and Its Discontents -- t1. The Pursuit of Guilty Things -- t2. The One and the Manor -- t3. Castes of Exception -- t4. Nothing Personal -- t5. Not World Enough -- tEpilogue: Everything Counts (Frankenstein) -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCorporate Romanticism offers an alternative history of the connections between modernity, individualism, and the novel. In early nineteenth-century England, two developments—the rise of corporate persons and the expanded scale of industrial action—undermined the basic assumption underpinning both liberalism and the law: that individual human persons can be meaningfully correlated with specific actions and particular effects. Reading works by Godwin, Austen, Hogg, Mary Shelley, and Dickens alongside a wide-ranging set of debates in nineteenth-century law and Romantic politics and aesthetics, Daniel Stout argues that the novel, a literary form long understood as a reflection of individualism’s ideological ascent, in fact registered the fragile fictionality of accountable individuals in a period defined by corporate actors and expansively entangled fields of action.Examining how liberalism, the law, and the novel all wrestled with the moral implications of a highly collectivized and densely packed modernity, Corporate Romanticism reconfigures our sense of the nineteenth century and its novels, arguing that we see in them not simply the apotheosis of laissez-fair individualism but the first chapter of a crucial and distinctly modern problem about how to fit the individualist and humanist terms of justice onto a world in which the most consequential agents are no longer persons.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIndividualism in literature. 0aJustice in literature. 0aLaw and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aModernism (Literature)zEngland. 0aRomanticism. 4aLaw. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aRomanticism.  aaction.  acharacter.  acorporate personhood.  aindustrialism.  ajustice.  alaw.  aliberalism.  athe corporation.  athe novel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311072902340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327226640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823272266423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823272266/original  a978-3-11-072902-3  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK